            <!-- Getting Started -->
            <section id="help-getting-started" class="help-section">
              <h2>Getting Started</h2>
              <p>Welcome to TruthCert-PairwisePro, a comprehensive meta-analysis platform.</p>

              <h3>Quick Start Guide</h3>
              <ol>
                <li><strong>Select Data Type:</strong> Choose from Binary, Continuous, HR, Proportion, Generic, or Correlation</li>
                <li><strong>Enter Study Data:</strong> Input your study data in the table or paste from Excel</li>
                <li><strong>Configure Analysis:</strong> Select effect measure, tau-squared estimator, and CI method</li>
                <li><strong>Run Analysis:</strong> Click "Run Analysis" to generate pooled estimates</li>
                <li><strong>Explore Results:</strong> Navigate through Analysis, Heterogeneity, Validation, and Verdict tabs</li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Supported Data Types</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Binary:</strong> Events/totals for treatment and control (2x2 table)</li>
                <li><strong>Continuous:</strong> Mean, SD, N for each group</li>
                <li><strong>Hazard Ratio:</strong> HR with confidence interval or standard error</li>
                <li><strong>Proportion:</strong> Single-arm events/N</li>
                <li><strong>Generic:</strong> Pre-calculated effect size (yi) and variance (vi)</li>
                <li><strong>Correlation:</strong> Correlation coefficient (r) and sample size (n)</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- Data Entry -->
            <section id="help-data-entry" class="help-section" style="display:none;">
              <h2>Data Entry</h2>

              <h3>Manual Entry</h3>
              <p>Enter study data row by row. Required fields depend on data type:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Binary:</strong> Study name, Events T, N T, Events C, N C</li>
                <li><strong>Continuous:</strong> Study name, Mean T, SD T, N T, Mean C, SD C, N C</li>
                <li><strong>HR:</strong> Study name, HR, Lower CI, Upper CI (or HR, SE)</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Paste from Excel</h3>
              <p>Copy data from Excel and paste directly into the data area. Column order should match the template headers.</p>

              <h3>Continuity Correction (Binary Data)</h3>
              <p>When zero cells exist in 2x2 tables:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Constant (0.5):</strong> Add 0.5 to all cells - most common</li>
                <li><strong>Treatment Arm:</strong> Add correction proportional to treatment allocation</li>
                <li><strong>Reciprocal:</strong> Add reciprocal of opposite arm size</li>
                <li><strong>Empirical:</strong> Data-driven correction</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- Analysis Methods -->
            <section id="help-analysis-methods" class="help-section" style="display:none;">
              <h2>Analysis Methods</h2>

              <h3>Fixed Effects (FE)</h3>
              <p>Assumes all studies estimate the same true effect. Weights by inverse variance only. Use when heterogeneity is low (I-squared less than 25%).</p>

              <h3>Random Effects (RE)</h3>
              <p>Assumes true effects vary across studies. Incorporates between-study variance (tau-squared). Recommended for most meta-analyses.</p>

              <h3>HKSJ Adjustment</h3>
              <p>Hartung-Knapp-Sidik-Jonkman adjustment uses t-distribution instead of normal, providing more accurate confidence intervals especially with few studies. Recommended when k less than 10.</p>

              <h3>Profile Likelihood CI</h3>
              <p>Alternative confidence interval method based on likelihood ratio. More accurate than Wald CIs when tau-squared is uncertain.</p>
            </section>

            <!-- Tau Estimators -->
            <section id="help-tau-estimators" class="help-section" style="display:none;">
              <h2>Tau-squared Estimators</h2>
              <p>Between-study variance can be estimated using several methods:</p>

              <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin:var(--space-3) 0;">
                <tr style="background:var(--surface-secondary);">
                  <th style="padding:var(--space-2);text-align:left;">Method</th>
                  <th style="padding:var(--space-2);text-align:left;">Best For</th>
                </tr>
                <tr><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);"><strong>DL (DerSimonian-Laird)</strong></td><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">Most common, good default</td></tr>
                <tr><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);"><strong>REML</strong></td><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">Best statistical properties, recommended</td></tr>
                <tr><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);"><strong>PM (Paule-Mandel)</strong></td><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">Iterative, unbiased for tau-squared</td></tr>
                <tr><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);"><strong>ML</strong></td><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">Maximum likelihood, slightly biased</td></tr>
                <tr><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);"><strong>EB (Empirical Bayes)</strong></td><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">When tau-squared expected to be small</td></tr>
                <tr><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);"><strong>SJ (Sidik-Jonkman)</strong></td><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">Better with few studies</td></tr>
                <tr><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);"><strong>HE (Hedges)</strong></td><td style="padding:var(--space-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">Unweighted, can be negative</td></tr>
                <tr><td style="padding:var(--space-2);"><strong>HS (Hunter-Schmidt)</strong></td><td style="padding:var(--space-2);">Psychology tradition</td></tr>
              </table>

              <p style="margin-top:var(--space-3);"><strong>Recommendation:</strong> Use REML with HKSJ adjustment for most analyses.</p>
            </section>

            <!-- Heterogeneity -->
            <section id="help-heterogeneity" class="help-section" style="display:none;">
              <h2>Heterogeneity</h2>

              <h3>I-squared</h3>
              <p>Percentage of variability due to heterogeneity (not sampling error):</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>0-25%:</strong> Low heterogeneity</li>
                <li><strong>25-50%:</strong> Moderate heterogeneity</li>
                <li><strong>50-75%:</strong> Substantial heterogeneity</li>
                <li><strong>75-100%:</strong> Considerable heterogeneity</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Tau-squared</h3>
              <p>Absolute between-study variance. Compare to within-study variances for context.</p>

              <h3>Q Statistic</h3>
              <p>Tests null hypothesis that all studies share same true effect. Significant Q suggests heterogeneity, but underpowered with few studies.</p>

              <h3>Prediction Interval</h3>
              <p>Range where 95% of future similar studies would fall. If it crosses null, effect direction uncertain.</p>

              <h3>When Heterogeneity is High</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>Explore subgroups or moderators</li>
                <li>Check for outliers (leave-one-out)</li>
                <li>Consider meta-regression</li>
                <li>Report prediction interval alongside CI</li>
              </ol>
            </section>

            <!-- Publication Bias -->
            <section id="help-publication-bias" class="help-section" style="display:none;">
              <h2>Publication Bias</h2>

              <h3>Funnel Plot</h3>
              <p>Plots effect size vs precision. Symmetric = no bias. Asymmetric = possible small-study effects or publication bias.</p>

              <h3>Statistical Tests</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Egger test:</strong> Regression of effects on SE. p less than 0.10 suggests asymmetry.</li>
                <li><strong>Begg test:</strong> Rank correlation. Less powerful than Egger.</li>
                <li><strong>Peters test:</strong> Better for binary outcomes (OR).</li>
                <li><strong>Harbord test:</strong> Modified test for log OR.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Adjustment Methods</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Trim and Fill:</strong> Estimates missing studies, imputes them, recalculates pooled effect.</li>
                <li><strong>PET-PEESE:</strong> Precision-Effect Test. If significant, use PEESE-adjusted estimate.</li>
                <li><strong>Selection Models:</strong> Model the selection process explicitly. Most sophisticated.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Interpretation Caution</h3>
              <p>Funnel asymmetry can have many causes beyond publication bias: true heterogeneity, methodological quality, chance with few studies.</p>
            </section>

            <!-- Bayesian -->
            <section id="help-bayesian" class="help-section" style="display:none;">
              <h2>Bayesian Analysis</h2>

              <h3>When to Use Bayesian</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Small number of studies (k less than 5)</li>
                <li>Want to incorporate prior knowledge</li>
                <li>Need probability statements about effect</li>
                <li>Assess publication bias (ModelAvg)</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Prior Specification</h3>
              <p>Priors affect results, especially with few studies:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Effect prior:</strong> Normal(0, SD). SD=0.5 is weakly informative for log-scale</li>
                <li><strong>Tau prior:</strong> Half-Cauchy or Half-Normal. Affects heterogeneity estimate.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Bayes Factors</h3>
              <p>Compare evidence for alternative vs null hypothesis:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>BF10 more than 10: Strong evidence for effect</li>
                <li>BF10 3-10: Moderate evidence</li>
                <li>BF10 1-3: Weak evidence</li>
                <li>BF10 less than 1: Evidence for null</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>ModelAvg (Robust Bayesian)</h3>
              <p>Averages across multiple models including selection models. Robust to publication bias and model uncertainty.</p>
            </section>

            <!-- Verdict System -->
            <section id="help-verdict" class="help-section" style="display:none;">
              <h2>TruthCert Verdict System</h2>

              <h3>Evidence Classifications</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong style="color:var(--color-success-500);">STABLE:</strong> Robust evidence. Effect consistent, precise, no major threats detected.</li>
                <li><strong style="color:var(--color-warning-500);">MODERATE:</strong> Generally reliable but some concerns. Interpret with caution.</li>
                <li><strong style="color:#f97316;">EXPOSED:</strong> Significant threats detected. Major uncertainty about true effect.</li>
                <li><strong style="color:var(--color-danger-500);">UNCERTAIN:</strong> Evidence too weak or conflicted for reliable conclusions.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>12-Point Threat Ledger</h3>
              <p>Systematic assessment of:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>Sample size adequacy</li>
                <li>Number of studies</li>
                <li>Heterogeneity level</li>
                <li>Publication bias indicators</li>
                <li>Statistical significance</li>
                <li>Prediction interval</li>
                <li>Sensitivity analysis stability</li>
                <li>Risk of bias concerns</li>
                <li>Effect size magnitude</li>
                <li>Confidence interval width</li>
                <li>GRADE certainty</li>
                <li>E-value (unmeasured confounding)</li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Severity Score</h3>
              <p>0-13 point scale aggregating all threats. Higher = more concern.</p>
            </section>

            <!-- Interpretation -->
            <section id="help-interpretation" class="help-section" style="display:none;">
              <h2>Interpreting Results</h2>

              <h3>Effect Size Interpretation (Binary)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>OR 1.0:</strong> No effect</li>
                <li><strong>OR 0.5-2.0:</strong> Small effect</li>
                <li><strong>OR 0.3-0.5 or 2-3:</strong> Moderate effect</li>
                <li><strong>OR less than 0.3 or more than 3:</strong> Large effect</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Effect Size Interpretation (Continuous)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>SMD 0.2:</strong> Small effect</li>
                <li><strong>SMD 0.5:</strong> Medium effect</li>
                <li><strong>SMD 0.8:</strong> Large effect</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Clinical Significance</h3>
              <p>Statistical significance is not clinical significance. Consider:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>NNT: How many patients need treatment for one to benefit?</li>
                <li>MCID: Does effect exceed minimum clinically important difference?</li>
                <li>Absolute risk: What is the actual risk reduction?</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- Export -->
            <section id="help-export" class="help-section" style="display:none;">
              <h2>Export Options</h2>

              <h3>Available Formats</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>CSV:</strong> Spreadsheet-compatible data export</li>
                <li><strong>Excel:</strong> Multi-sheet workbook with all results</li>
                <li><strong>YAML:</strong> Machine-readable structured format</li>
                <li><strong>JSON:</strong> Session state for sharing/restoring</li>
                <li><strong>PDF Report:</strong> Formatted report with all visualizations</li>
                <li><strong>R Script:</strong> Reproducible analysis code for metafor</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Saving Sessions</h3>
              <p>Use "Save Session" to export current state as JSON. Load later with "Load Session".</p>
            </section>

            <!-- Glossary -->
            <section id="help-glossary" class="help-section" style="display:none;">
              <h2>Glossary</h2>

              <dl style="line-height:1.8;">
                <dt><strong>CI (Confidence Interval)</strong></dt>
                <dd>Range that contains the true effect with 95% probability (frequentist interpretation).</dd>

                <dt><strong>Effect Size</strong></dt>
                <dd>Standardized measure of treatment effect (OR, RR, SMD, HR, etc.)</dd>

                <dt><strong>GRADE</strong></dt>
                <dd>Grading of Recommendations Assessment, Development and Evaluation - evidence quality framework.</dd>

                <dt><strong>Heterogeneity</strong></dt>
                <dd>Variation in true effects across studies beyond sampling error.</dd>

                <dt><strong>HKSJ</strong></dt>
                <dd>Hartung-Knapp-Sidik-Jonkman - adjustment using t-distribution for CIs.</dd>

                <dt><strong>I-squared</strong></dt>
                <dd>Proportion of total variability due to heterogeneity (0-100%).</dd>

                <dt><strong>NNT</strong></dt>
                <dd>Number Needed to Treat - patients needed for one to benefit.</dd>

                <dt><strong>Prediction Interval</strong></dt>
                <dd>Range where 95% of future study effects would fall.</dd>

                <dt><strong>REML</strong></dt>
                <dd>Restricted Maximum Likelihood - preferred tau-squared estimator.</dd>

                <dt><strong>ModelAvg</strong></dt>
                <dd>Robust Bayesian Meta-Analysis - model averaging approach.</dd>

                <dt><strong>Tau-squared</strong></dt>
                <dd>Between-study variance in random effects models.</dd>

                <dt><strong>Trim and Fill</strong></dt>
                <dd>Method to estimate and impute missing studies due to publication bias.</dd>
              </dl>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section id="help-faq" class="help-section" style="display:none;">
              <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

              <details style="margin-bottom:var(--space-3);">
                <summary style="cursor:pointer;font-weight:600;">Which tau-squared estimator should I use?</summary>
                <p style="padding:var(--space-2);color:var(--text-secondary);">REML is recommended for most analyses. It has good statistical properties and is widely accepted. DerSimonian-Laird is most common but can underestimate tau-squared.</p>
              </details>

              <details style="margin-bottom:var(--space-3);">
                <summary style="cursor:pointer;font-weight:600;">Should I use HKSJ adjustment?</summary>
                <p style="padding:var(--space-2);color:var(--text-secondary);">Yes, especially with fewer than 10 studies. It provides more accurate confidence intervals by using a t-distribution and accounting for uncertainty in tau-squared.</p>
              </details>

              <details style="margin-bottom:var(--space-3);">
                <summary style="cursor:pointer;font-weight:600;">My funnel plot is asymmetric - is there publication bias?</summary>
                <p style="padding:var(--space-2);color:var(--text-secondary);">Not necessarily. Asymmetry can be due to true heterogeneity, study quality differences, or chance (especially with few studies). Combine with statistical tests and consider the context.</p>
              </details>

              <details style="margin-bottom:var(--space-3);">
                <summary style="cursor:pointer;font-weight:600;">What does a wide prediction interval mean?</summary>
                <p style="padding:var(--space-2);color:var(--text-secondary);">High heterogeneity. Even if the pooled effect is significant, individual settings may show very different effects. Report the prediction interval alongside the confidence interval.</p>
              </details>

              <details style="margin-bottom:var(--space-3);">
                <summary style="cursor:pointer;font-weight:600;">How do I handle zero events?</summary>
                <p style="padding:var(--space-2);color:var(--text-secondary);">Use continuity correction (0.5 added to all cells is common). Alternatively, use exact methods or Peto OR for rare events. Consider if studies with zero events in both arms should be excluded.</p>
              </details>

              <details style="margin-bottom:var(--space-3);">
                <summary style="cursor:pointer;font-weight:600;">When should I use Bayesian analysis?</summary>
                <p style="padding:var(--space-2);color:var(--text-secondary);">With very few studies (k less than 5), when you want probability statements, or when incorporating prior knowledge. ModelAvg is useful for publication bias-adjusted estimates.</p>
              </details>
            </section>

          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

